# Applied AI & ML Essentials Capstone Project - Part 2

## Supervised Machine Learning Model

## Project Overview

This project focuses on building and evaluating supervised machine learning models using the cleaned dataset created in Part 1.

Two models were developed:

1. Regression Model - Predicting average glucose level
2. Classification Model - Predicting stroke occurrence

## Dataset

The dataset used is the cleaned Stroke Prediction Dataset from Part 1.

The dataset contains health and demographic information of patients including:

- Age
- Gender
- Hypertension
- Heart Disease
- Work Type
- Residence Type
- BMI
- Average Glucose Level
- Smoking Status
- Stroke

## Target Variables

### Regression Target

The regression target selected was:

`avg_glucose_level`

The model predicts the glucose level based on patient features.

### Classification Target

The classification target selected was:

`stroke`

The model predicts whether a patient has stroke or not.

## Data Preprocessing

- Loaded the cleaned dataset using pandas.
- Removed target columns from the feature set.
- Converted categorical variables using one-hot encoding.
- Applied StandardScaler for feature scaling.
- The scaler was fitted only on training data to avoid data leakage.

## Regression Models

### Linear Regression

A Linear Regression model was trained and evaluated using:

- Mean Squared Error (MSE)
- R² Score

### Ridge Regression

Ridge Regression with alpha = 1.0 was also trained and compared with Linear Regression.

Ridge regression helps reduce overfitting by applying L2 regularization.

## Classification Model

### Logistic Regression

A Logistic Regression model was used for stroke prediction.

Class imbalance was handled using:

`class_weight='balanced'`

The model was evaluated using:

- Confusion Matrix
- Accuracy
- Precision
- Recall
- F1 Score
- ROC Curve
- AUC Score

## Threshold Analysis

Prediction probabilities were generated using `predict_proba()`.

Different classification thresholds between 0.30 and 0.70 were tested to compare:

- Precision
- Recall
- F1 Score

## Regularization Experiment

A second Logistic Regression model was trained using:

`C = 0.01`

The performance was compared with the baseline model using:

`C = 1.0`

